1
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:53,240
 So how long's this been going on for?

2
00:01:54,080 --> 00:01:55,559
 l don't know.

3
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:57,079
 A few weeks?

4
00:01:57,080 --> 00:02:00,080
 - A long time.
 - A year?

5
00:02:02,280 --> 00:02:03,999
 l suppose so.

6
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:05,639
 A whole year?

7
00:02:05,640 --> 00:02:08,640
 You've taken your time to come
 and see me, haven't you?

8
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:10,479
 You think it's going to stop, don't you?

9
00:02:10,480 --> 00:02:12,319
 l'll just take your blood pressure.

10
00:02:12,320 --> 00:02:15,319
 Can you pop your arm on the desk
 for me?

11
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:16,639
 There you go.

12
00:02:16,640 --> 00:02:19,640
 lf you straighten it up
 and push up your sleeve...

13
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:22,800
 Are you dozing in the daytime?

14
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:25,759
 Sometimes.

15
00:02:25,760 --> 00:02:28,359
 So, l just need something
 to help me sleep.

16
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:31,079
 l know. How much sleep
 are you getting at night?

17
00:02:31,080 --> 00:02:33,199
 l'm not getting any. That's why l'm here.

18
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:35,759
 l understand, sweetheart.

19
00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:38,760
 OK. lt's just going to go tight.

20
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:41,800
 (puffing)

21
00:02:45,320 --> 00:02:48,320
 (hissing)

22
00:02:52,040 --> 00:02:55,040
 Have you got any particular worries
 at the moment?

23
00:02:56,360 --> 00:02:58,319
 No financial problems?

24
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:01,320
 No. l don't know
 what that's got to do with it.

25
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:04,599
 What about at home?

26
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:07,600
 How are things with husband?

27
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:12,360
 OK, if you just lean forward and take a
 few deep breaths, in through your mouth.

28
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:24,600
 And again.

29
00:03:30,320 --> 00:03:33,320
 lt's lovely and clear.

30
00:03:33,760 --> 00:03:36,760
 - Have you got any kids?
 - Yes.

31
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:39,960
 - Are they still at home with you?
 - Son is, works with his father.

32
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:42,919
 Daughter's left, only see her
 when she wants something.

33
00:03:42,920 --> 00:03:45,920
 And how about you?
 Have you started your menopause?

34
00:03:46,160 --> 00:03:48,039
 Yes.

35
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:51,040
 Everything OK?

36
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:54,999
 So, will you give me some sleeping tablets?

37
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,399
 Maybe, but it might not solve your problem.

38
00:03:57,400 --> 00:03:59,759
 Give me a night's sleep, though,
 wouldn't it?

39
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:02,760
 - How much alcohol are you drinking?
 - l don't drink. My husband drinks.

40
00:04:03,120 --> 00:04:04,519
 ls it a problem?

41
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:07,519
 No.

42
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:10,520
 Are you taking any drugs, medication?

43
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:12,279
 How about coffee?

44
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:14,399
 Are you drinking a lot to keep awake?

45
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:15,799
 Coffee, yes.

46
00:04:15,800 --> 00:04:16,919
 - Tea?
 - Yes.

47
00:04:16,920 --> 00:04:19,920
 Well, we might have to look at that,
 mightn't we?

48
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:24,439
 OK.

49
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:27,440
 Your blood pressure is slightly up,
 but l'm not overly concerned about that.

50
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:31,200
 But l do want you to have a blood test,
 to check your thyroid.

51
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:34,199
 You can make an appointment at reception.
 All right?

52
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:36,359
 Yes.

53
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:39,360
 Now, l will give you something to help
 you sleep but just enough for a week.

54
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:45,479
 - What good's that?
 - lnsomnia isn't a disease.

55
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:48,480
 Sleeping tablets won't make it go away.
 We need to find the cause.

56
00:04:49,880 --> 00:04:52,880
 Now, you're obviously anxious,
 and a little depressed.

57
00:04:54,320 --> 00:04:57,320
 So l want you to come back
 and speak to our counsellor.

58
00:04:58,920 --> 00:05:01,920
 - What for?
 - l think she'd be able to help you.

59
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:06,839
 But you'll give me the prescription now?

60
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:09,840
 Yes, but will you see the counsellor?

61
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:12,920
 l think it will do you some good.

62
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:16,359
 You think about it for a moment.

63
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:19,360
 (tapping of keyboard)

64
00:05:39,880 --> 00:05:41,599
 Tom!

65
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:44,600
 Give us it.

66
00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:15,880
 (sighs)

67
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:29,439
 - Don't do your back in.
 - l know.

68
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:32,440
 lt doesn't get any easier.
 Job for a younger man, this.

69
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:35,799
 Joe used to love it here.

70
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:38,359
 Did you speak to my son and heir?

71
00:06:38,360 --> 00:06:40,559
 l left him a message on his answerphone.

72
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:42,519
 (panting)

73
00:06:42,520 --> 00:06:45,520
 lt's going to rain again.

74
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:28,240
 (machinery whirs)

75
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:33,159
 - Now, then.
 - Hello, boss.

76
00:07:33,160 --> 00:07:35,959
 - What you got?
 - You hit rock, then?

77
00:07:35,960 --> 00:07:38,960
 Yeah, we just gone through.
 This is the fourth, so l reckon, what, 1 71/2?

78
00:07:39,400 --> 00:07:40,479
 Give or take.

79
00:07:40,480 --> 00:07:43,480
 - 1 71/2? lt's got to be a scour hollow.
 - Probably.

80
00:07:43,560 --> 00:07:45,079
 - All right, Mick?
 - All right.

81
00:07:45,080 --> 00:07:48,080
 Hello.

82
00:07:53,960 --> 00:07:55,959
 How long will it take us to get back?

83
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:58,719
 - 25, with traffic. Are you hungry?
 - l am.

84
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:00,999
 Good.

85
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,719
 There you go.

86
00:08:03,720 --> 00:08:05,799
 Yes, London clay. Thank you.

87
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:07,559
 - Thanks, Andy. See you.
 - Cheers.

88
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:10,560
 Ta-ta.

89
00:08:26,840 --> 00:08:29,639
 - Dusting of mica.
 - Let's have a look.

90
00:08:29,640 --> 00:08:32,640
 Hmm, it's quite nice.

91
00:08:33,960 --> 00:08:36,679
 (chuckles)

92
00:08:36,680 --> 00:08:39,680
 Very nice.

93
00:08:41,640 --> 00:08:44,640
 - lt's just a dusting, isn't it?
 - Yeah.

94
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:53,880
 What would you say was the happiest
 moment in your life?

95
00:08:54,760 --> 00:08:56,919
 What do you mean?

96
00:08:56,920 --> 00:08:59,920
 Your nicest memory.

97
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:03,360
 Have a think.

98
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:16,720
 When your children were born?

99
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:23,160
 - Your wedding day?
 - l don't know.

100
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:25,799
 Take your time.

101
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:27,559
 l can't remember.

102
00:09:27,560 --> 00:09:30,399
 - Can't or won't?
 - Mm?

103
00:09:30,400 --> 00:09:32,039
 Can't or won't remember?

104
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:34,959
 Don't know what l'm doing here.
 l didn't want to come.

105
00:09:34,960 --> 00:09:37,239
 Don't want to talk about my family.
 Why should l?

106
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:40,079
 None of your business.
 All l need is a good night's sleep

107
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:41,839
 and nobody's helping me.

108
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:44,840
 Janet, l want to help you.
 That's why we're here.

109
00:09:45,840 --> 00:09:48,840
 l know it's not easy
 to talk about personal things.

110
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:52,920
 Suppose the boot was on the other foot,
 and someone came to you,

111
00:09:54,120 --> 00:09:57,120
 say, your daughter, and said,
 ''l haven't been sleeping for months.''

112
00:09:58,920 --> 00:10:00,839
 What would you say to them?

113
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:02,799
 ''Go to the doctor.''

114
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:05,800
 What else would you say?

115
00:10:06,280 --> 00:10:08,519
 l don't know.

116
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:11,520
 What would you ask her?

117
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:15,360
 ls she eating all right?
 l don't know, something like that.

118
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:18,679
 Good.

119
00:10:18,680 --> 00:10:21,680
 Anything else?

120
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:25,119
 That a couple of months of proper sleep
 would sort it out.

121
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:27,799
 Sort what out?

122
00:10:27,800 --> 00:10:29,559
 The sleeping.

123
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:32,560
 OK.

124
00:10:34,440 --> 00:10:37,440
 On a scale of one to ten...

125
00:10:38,080 --> 00:10:40,199
 ..how happy
 would you say you are, Janet?

126
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:43,079
 - One.
 - One.

127
00:10:43,080 --> 00:10:46,080
 l think there's room for improvement there,
 don't you?

128
00:10:46,120 --> 00:10:49,120
 What is the one thing that would improve
 your life, apart from sleep?

129
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:53,640
 - A different life.
 - A different life.

130
00:10:55,720 --> 00:10:58,720
 Change is frightening, isn't it?

131
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:03,920
 Nothing changes.

132
00:11:05,560 --> 00:11:07,999
 Hope to see you next week, Janet.
 Same time.

133
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,639
 l'll be here, but it's up to you. No pressure.

134
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:13,319
 Bye.

135
00:11:13,320 --> 00:11:16,320
 (sighs)

136
00:11:19,800 --> 00:11:22,800
 - Bye-bye, Sam.
 - Bye.

137
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:28,439
 Look at you!

138
00:11:28,440 --> 00:11:30,159
 You look like you're fit to burst.

139
00:11:30,160 --> 00:11:32,999
 l am fit to burst.
 Big boy's wrestling his way down.

140
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:35,159
 lf he pops out, give me a shout.

141
00:11:35,160 --> 00:11:38,160
 Sweetheart, l'll do more than shout.

142
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:42,399
 - Hi, Gerri.
 - Hello, Mary.

143
00:11:42,400 --> 00:11:44,919
 You're a sight for sore eyes.

144
00:11:44,920 --> 00:11:47,920
 - Can you process these for me?
 - Oh, well, seeing as it's you.

145
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:50,719
 - How are you?
 - l'm snowed under, to be honest,

146
00:11:50,720 --> 00:11:52,399
 and l've got a headache.

147
00:11:52,400 --> 00:11:54,559
 - Have you seen the doctor?
 - (laughs)

148
00:11:54,560 --> 00:11:55,879
 Hello, Gemma.

149
00:11:55,880 --> 00:11:57,679
 Do you fancy a drink tonight?

150
00:11:57,680 --> 00:11:59,319
 - l'd love one.
 - Great. Are you sure?

151
00:11:59,320 --> 00:12:01,319
 - l've only got an hour.
 - That's all right.

152
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:03,519
 - Tom's cooking supper.
 - Oh, lovely.

153
00:12:03,520 --> 00:12:06,520
 - l'll see you later.
 - Yeah.

154
00:12:08,120 --> 00:12:11,120
 (rain pouring)

155
00:12:13,880 --> 00:12:16,880
 (buzz of conversation)

156
00:12:19,320 --> 00:12:22,199
 Do you know, Gerri, l've never been with
 a man who could cook.

157
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:24,079
 - Haven't you?
 - No.

158
00:12:24,080 --> 00:12:26,839
 - They could do other things.
 - That doesn't get you fed.

159
00:12:26,840 --> 00:12:29,279
 No, it keeps a girl happy, though.
 (laughs)

160
00:12:29,280 --> 00:12:31,719
 - And you can't cook.
 - No. Well, l can a bit.

161
00:12:31,720 --> 00:12:34,279
 - But it's not really my thing.
 - No, it's not.

162
00:12:34,280 --> 00:12:36,599
 Oh, no, don't remind me about that,
 Gerri.

163
00:12:36,600 --> 00:12:37,719
 (laughs)

164
00:12:37,720 --> 00:12:40,159
 You could put an ad in the paper
 ''Chefwanted''.

165
00:12:40,160 --> 00:12:43,160
 Yeah. ''Chef/boyfriend
 required for gorgeous girl.''

166
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:46,759
 No, ''Mature woman with cat.''

167
00:12:46,760 --> 00:12:48,679
 (laughter)

168
00:12:48,680 --> 00:12:51,680
 No, ''Maturish''.
 We don't want to put them off, do we?

169
00:12:58,080 --> 00:13:00,799
 lt's lovely the way you and Tom
 do everything together.

170
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:03,800
 - We're very lucky.
 - Yeah. You are, but you deserve it.

171
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 - You're both such lovely people.
 - Oops, my halo's slipping.

172
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:10,199
 Yeah, Saint Gerri.

173
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:13,200
 No, but l'm really comfortable
 with where l am in my life, as you know.

174
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:16,279
 l've got my lovely little garden flat,
 a good job.

175
00:13:16,280 --> 00:13:19,280
 l've got my health, touch wood,
 l've got my independence.

176
00:13:19,640 --> 00:13:22,199
 l mean, don't get me wrong, it's not all rosy.

177
00:13:22,200 --> 00:13:25,200
 l have good days and bad days
 like everyone else, but, hey!

178
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:28,079
 Are you going to do something
 about your garden?

179
00:13:28,080 --> 00:13:30,719
 Oh, don't remind me!
 l'm really guilty about that.

180
00:13:30,720 --> 00:13:33,159
 - l've neglected it, haven't l?
 - Yes, you have.

181
00:13:33,160 --> 00:13:36,160
 But yesterday l was brushing my teeth
 and l looked out the window

182
00:13:36,600 --> 00:13:39,600
 and l saw these two daffodils
 peeping over the top ofthe grass.

183
00:13:39,800 --> 00:13:41,079
 l must get it cut.

184
00:13:41,080 --> 00:13:43,039
 - Get yourselfthat lawn mower.
 - l know.

185
00:13:43,040 --> 00:13:45,719
 Couldn't l just get a man in?
 lt wouldn't cost much.

186
00:13:45,720 --> 00:13:48,720
 - Hmm. ''Gardener/chef/ boyfriend.''
 - Yeah! (laughs)

187
00:13:50,120 --> 00:13:53,120
 But l don't want to spend too much money
 because l'm going to get myself a little car.

188
00:13:54,760 --> 00:13:57,239
 - Are you?
 - Yeah, l've decided it's about time.

189
00:13:57,240 --> 00:13:59,639
 - lt's a big step.
 - l know. lt's exciting, isn't it?

190
00:13:59,640 --> 00:14:02,559
 l mean, l've got a little bit of money.
 Not a lot, but enough.

191
00:14:02,560 --> 00:14:04,919
 But l'll have to cut back on, you know,

192
00:14:04,920 --> 00:14:07,519
 shoes, clothes, jewellery,
 my knick-knacky things.

193
00:14:07,520 --> 00:14:10,520
 But that's OK because l've got loads of
 clothes. My wardrobe isn't big enough.

194
00:14:11,360 --> 00:14:14,360
 ln fact, l'm not doing anything this
 weekend, so l'll get up really early,

195
00:14:15,080 --> 00:14:18,080
 sort my winter clothes into plastic bags
 and shove them under the bed.

196
00:14:19,320 --> 00:14:21,559
 - Can l top you up?
 - No, l'm going now, Mary.

197
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:23,559
 - Won't you help me finish it?
 - No, really.

198
00:14:23,560 --> 00:14:26,560
 - Oh, all right. Well, l think l'm going to
 stay for a little while.

199
00:14:29,480 --> 00:14:31,799
 How's Joe?
 Have you heard from him this week?

200
00:14:31,800 --> 00:14:34,319
 - No, but l'm sure he's fine.
 - Still no girlfriend?

201
00:14:34,320 --> 00:14:36,279
 l've no idea.

202
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:39,280
 He must have something on the go,
 a good-looking boy like him.

203
00:14:39,640 --> 00:14:41,159
 - See you on Thursday.
 - Oh!

204
00:14:41,160 --> 00:14:42,879
 You're coming for supper on Saturday.

205
00:14:42,880 --> 00:14:45,599
 Oh, lovely. Thank you, Gerri.
 Give my love to that lovely Tom.

206
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:48,600
 - l will. You take care.
 - Yeah.

207
00:14:57,560 --> 00:15:00,560
 Sorry l'm late. l'm sorry.

208
00:15:34,040 --> 00:15:35,879
 What's for supper?

209
00:15:35,880 --> 00:15:38,399
 Arrabbiata. Are you hungry?

210
00:15:38,400 --> 00:15:41,039
 l'm starving.

211
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:43,599
 Hello.

212
00:15:43,600 --> 00:15:45,639
 Have a taste.

213
00:15:45,640 --> 00:15:47,479
 l hope it's not too hot.

214
00:15:47,480 --> 00:15:50,480
 You can never tell with chillies.

215
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:55,439
 - No.
 - No?

216
00:15:55,440 --> 00:15:57,399
 Oh, it's coming out my ears.

217
00:15:57,400 --> 00:16:00,400
 Good. Glass ofwine?

218
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:03,039
 No, l've had a couple.
 Oh, go on, just a smidgeon.

219
00:16:03,040 --> 00:16:06,040
 That's the spirit.

220
00:16:06,160 --> 00:16:09,160
 - How was your day?
 - Good.

221
00:16:09,400 --> 00:16:12,400
 l was out and about, getting my hands dirty.

222
00:16:12,760 --> 00:16:15,079
 - How about you?
 - Disappointing.

223
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:17,159
 Pass me the parsley.

224
00:16:17,160 --> 00:16:18,519
 No breakthroughs?

225
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:20,919
 l had my alcoholic tutor in again.

226
00:16:20,920 --> 00:16:22,279
 Yeah?

227
00:16:22,280 --> 00:16:25,280
 - He was pissed as a fart.
 - Really?

228
00:16:25,840 --> 00:16:28,479
 lt was very upsetting, actually.

229
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:30,119
 How did you handle it?

230
00:16:30,120 --> 00:16:32,719
 l bought him a double Scotch.
 No, l had to challenge him.

231
00:16:32,720 --> 00:16:34,879
 l told him it was up to him.

232
00:16:34,880 --> 00:16:36,759
 How did he take that?

233
00:16:36,760 --> 00:16:38,759
 Well, l don't know. We'll have to see.

234
00:16:38,760 --> 00:16:41,079
 - Well, at least he came.
 - Hmm.

235
00:16:41,080 --> 00:16:43,599
 - Have we heard from Joe?
 - No.

236
00:16:43,600 --> 00:16:45,519
 But l haven't checked my e-mails.

237
00:16:45,520 --> 00:16:48,199
 l'll ring him later. l'd love to see him.

238
00:16:48,200 --> 00:16:51,200
 He's all right.

239
00:16:54,080 --> 00:16:55,959
 Mr Gupta?

240
00:16:55,960 --> 00:16:57,719
 Joe Hepple, nice to meet you.

241
00:16:57,720 --> 00:16:59,519
 - l just came with him.
 - Ah, good.

242
00:16:59,520 --> 00:17:02,520
 Just follow me this way, please.

243
00:17:03,720 --> 00:17:06,720
 This way.

244
00:17:16,400 --> 00:17:19,279
 Excuse the mess.

245
00:17:19,280 --> 00:17:22,280
 You sit there, Mr Gupta,
 and...l'll pop you there.

246
00:17:31,640 --> 00:17:34,640
 OK, now we've opened all these letters,

247
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:38,000
 and l've seen all l need to see
 for the time being.

248
00:17:38,880 --> 00:17:41,359
 Obviously, it's a sizeable correspondence

249
00:17:41,360 --> 00:17:44,360
 and, understandably, Mr Gupta hasn't
 exactly been in a position to open them,

250
00:17:45,600 --> 00:17:48,239
 seeing as he's been in hospital
 for the past ten weeks.

251
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:51,240
 But, you're looking fit and raring to go,
 Mr Gupta.

252
00:17:51,640 --> 00:17:52,959
 Huh?

253
00:17:52,960 --> 00:17:55,960
 (mouths)

254
00:17:56,360 --> 00:17:57,879
 WOMAN: Excuse me.
 - Hm?

255
00:17:57,880 --> 00:18:00,199
 - How long will this take?
 JOE: Not too long.

256
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:03,159
 lt's just l have to get back to work.

257
00:18:03,160 --> 00:18:04,559
 What do you do?

258
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:07,559
 Er, l'm... Restaurant family business.

259
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:09,559
 Oh, tasty.

260
00:18:09,560 --> 00:18:11,479
 OK.

261
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:14,480
 Erm...it's important for Mr Gupta
 to understand that at this point

262
00:18:16,440 --> 00:18:18,799
 he's in no danger of being evicted.

263
00:18:18,800 --> 00:18:21,800
 (speaks Hindustani)

264
00:18:22,400 --> 00:18:23,599
 Acha?

265
00:18:23,600 --> 00:18:26,600
 (continues in Hindustani)

266
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:29,239
 OK?

267
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:31,999
 l'll take you briefly through
 what is going to happen in court.

268
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 Erm...l'll be representing Mr Gupta
 on the day.

269
00:18:35,240 --> 00:18:37,239
 We'll put the case to the judge...

270
00:18:37,240 --> 00:18:38,879
 - (phone rings)
 - ..and...

271
00:18:38,880 --> 00:18:41,880
 he will agree to adjourn which will then
 give us time to sort things out, OK?

272
00:18:43,520 --> 00:18:45,839
 So, l'll... Excuse me.

273
00:18:45,840 --> 00:18:48,840
 Hello?

274
00:19:09,960 --> 00:19:12,960
 (knocks on door)

275
00:19:14,400 --> 00:19:17,239
 - l'll get it!
 TOM: All right.

276
00:19:17,240 --> 00:19:18,839
 - Hello, Mary.
 - Hi, Gerri.

277
00:19:18,840 --> 00:19:20,999
 - lt's stopped raining, thank goodness.
 - l know.

278
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:22,679
 - Welcome.
 - Oh, thank you.

279
00:19:22,680 --> 00:19:24,439
 l bought you a little present, some thyme.

280
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:26,519
 - That's lovely. Thank you.
 - lt's nothing much.

281
00:19:26,520 --> 00:19:27,959
 - Oh, there he is.
 - Hello, love.

282
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:29,599
 Hello, Tom.

283
00:19:29,600 --> 00:19:31,679
 Oh! l'm sorry, l just had to have a cigarette

284
00:19:31,680 --> 00:19:34,039
 - and l know you don't like the smell.
 - Don't be daft.

285
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:36,439
 - l'm trying to give up, aren't l, Gerri?
 - Oh, are you?

286
00:19:36,440 --> 00:19:38,559
 Only l've just had a bad experience
 on the tube.

287
00:19:38,560 --> 00:19:40,599
 - What happened?
 - There was this man.

288
00:19:40,600 --> 00:19:42,839
 - What did he do?
 - Well, he was looking at me.

289
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:45,840
 l mean, every time l looked up,
 he was looking at me.

290
00:19:46,520 --> 00:19:48,839
 - Oh, dear.
 - lt was a bit unsettling, to be honest.

291
00:19:48,840 --> 00:19:50,359
 Well, you're here now.

292
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:53,360
 Exactly, and l'm very happy
 to be here with both of you.

293
00:19:53,400 --> 00:19:55,079
 This is for you, Tom.

294
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:56,759
 - Ah!
 - lt's nothing special.

295
00:19:56,760 --> 00:19:57,999
 Buenos Aires.

296
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 Yeah, because l thought you went there,
 didn't you, the two of you, Argentina?

297
00:20:01,720 --> 00:20:03,399
 - No, we didn't, no.
 - No.

298
00:20:03,400 --> 00:20:04,759
 - Didn't you?
 - No.

299
00:20:04,760 --> 00:20:06,999
 Tom's been to Brazil, digging his holes.

300
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 - Yeah.
 - Oh, l'm so stupid sometimes.

301
00:20:10,280 --> 00:20:12,159
 - That's all right.
 - Oh, honestly,

302
00:20:12,160 --> 00:20:14,359
 Pow! What are you going to do with me,
 eh?

303
00:20:14,360 --> 00:20:17,360
 l'm just going to run upstairs.
 ls that all right? l won't be a minute.

304
00:20:23,960 --> 00:20:26,960
 - l haven't seen you since Christmas.
 - Really?

305
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:29,919
 - Oh, it's just the three of us tonight?
 - Yes.

306
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:32,079
 - l did tell you.
 - Did you?

307
00:20:32,080 --> 00:20:34,759
 - Mm.
 - We wanted you all to ourselves, Mary.

308
00:20:34,760 --> 00:20:37,760
 Oh, thank you, Tom.
 That's what all the boys say.

309
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:40,479
 No, l wasn't sure what to wear.

310
00:20:40,480 --> 00:20:43,279
 l didn't know if it was going to be
 one of your big dinner parties,

311
00:20:43,280 --> 00:20:46,280
 - or just us, you know, casual.
 - l think you got it just about right, Mary.

312
00:20:46,720 --> 00:20:49,479
 - You look lovely.
 - Oh, thank you, Gerri.

313
00:20:49,480 --> 00:20:52,480
 - (yawns) Oh...sorry.
 - Did you have a late night?

314
00:20:52,960 --> 00:20:55,960
 Oh! l stayed up watching the film.

315
00:20:56,800 --> 00:20:58,599
 l couldn't wake up this morning.

316
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:00,839
 No, but it was lovely having a lie-in
 on my day off.

317
00:21:00,840 --> 00:21:02,199
 - We stayed in.
 - Did you?

318
00:21:02,200 --> 00:21:05,200
 - We listened to some music.
 - Amongst other things.

319
00:21:05,680 --> 00:21:07,879
 - l thought Joe might be coming.
 - l don't think so.

320
00:21:07,880 --> 00:21:10,880
 - He's coming tomorrow.
 - Oh, that's a shame. l won't see him.

321
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,119
 Did Gerri tell you about me getting a car, Tom?

322
00:21:13,120 --> 00:21:14,119
 Yes.

323
00:21:14,120 --> 00:21:16,759
 - What do you think?
 - Exciting. What are you going to get?

324
00:21:16,760 --> 00:21:19,760
 Oh, well, l don't know.
 Something small and...red.

325
00:21:21,080 --> 00:21:23,919
 Small and red?
 Well, that narrows it down.

326
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:26,159
 - Yeah.
 - l hope you're hungry.

327
00:21:26,160 --> 00:21:28,919
 - l'm starving, Gerri, you know me.
 - We'll have to fatten you up.

328
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:31,199
 Oh, it's lovely having your dinner cooked
 for you.

329
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:33,559
 You don't really bother
 when you're by yourself.

330
00:21:33,560 --> 00:21:35,239
 - You look well.
 - Oh, thank you, Tom.

331
00:21:35,240 --> 00:21:36,799
 You're nice and slim.

332
00:21:36,800 --> 00:21:38,759
 Am l?
 Well, l've always been slim, haven't l?

333
00:21:38,760 --> 00:21:41,719
 - Unlike me. Middle-aged spread.
 - Shut up.

334
00:21:41,720 --> 00:21:43,479
 You're perfect. Gorgeous in every way.

335
00:21:43,480 --> 00:21:46,480
 And you know it.

336
00:21:50,840 --> 00:21:53,840
 Sit yourself down, Mary.
 Help yourselfto another drink.

337
00:21:56,120 --> 00:21:58,319
 How is that dressing coming along?

338
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:01,320
 As well as can be expected.

339
00:22:12,240 --> 00:22:14,959
 l hear you're going to the Emerald lsle again,
 Tom.

340
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:17,959
 That's correct. Rent a cottage, take the car.

341
00:22:17,960 --> 00:22:20,879
 - Put the tent in the back.
 - And the sleeping bags.

342
00:22:20,880 --> 00:22:23,880
 - lf it's nice we might do a bit of camping.
 - Oh, no.

343
00:22:24,080 --> 00:22:27,080
 l wouldn't fancy sleeping in a tent,
 thank you very much.

344
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:30,280
 No, l never had you down
 as one of nature's Girl Guides, Mary.

345
00:22:31,320 --> 00:22:33,839
 No, Tom.

346
00:22:33,840 --> 00:22:36,840
 But l am always prepared.

347
00:22:37,440 --> 00:22:40,199
 - Yes, but what for?
 - For anything, Gerri.

348
00:22:40,200 --> 00:22:42,079
 - You know me.
 - Yes, l do.

349
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:44,519
 (laughter)

350
00:22:44,520 --> 00:22:47,520
 l'm not going to get a holiday this year.

351
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 But then l never do, do l, Gerri?
 Because l haven't got anyone to go with.

352
00:22:53,440 --> 00:22:56,319
 lt's all right for you two,
 you've got each other.

353
00:22:56,320 --> 00:22:59,320
 We're going to the Ring of Kerry.

354
00:23:00,720 --> 00:23:02,279
 The what?

355
00:23:02,280 --> 00:23:04,319
 - The Ring of Kerry. lt's an area.
 GERRl: Tralee,

356
00:23:04,320 --> 00:23:06,279
 - Dingle Bay.
 - Oh, lovely.

357
00:23:06,280 --> 00:23:08,119
 You've been there before, haven't you?

358
00:23:08,120 --> 00:23:10,239
 - That was Donegal.
 - Oh.

359
00:23:10,240 --> 00:23:12,439
 The geologist stands on the beach

360
00:23:12,440 --> 00:23:15,159
 with his back to the sea and looks at the cliffs

361
00:23:15,160 --> 00:23:18,160
 whilst the geologist's wife stands on the beach

362
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:21,480
 with her back to the cliffs
 looking at the sea.

363
00:23:24,720 --> 00:23:27,720
 You see, l can't afford to buy my car
 and have a holiday.

364
00:23:31,080 --> 00:23:34,080
 But, if l had more money,
 then l could do both.

365
00:23:36,240 --> 00:23:39,240
 But when you've got your car, Mary,
 you'll be able to go wherever you want,

366
00:23:39,600 --> 00:23:41,799
 - very reasonably.
 - Exactly, Tom.

367
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:44,039
 That's exactly why l'm getting it.

368
00:23:44,040 --> 00:23:47,040
 You see, l like just taking off
 and escaping, don't l, Gerri?

369
00:23:49,400 --> 00:23:50,839
 Hm.

370
00:23:50,840 --> 00:23:53,840
 l feel like l'm being somebody else.

371
00:23:54,200 --> 00:23:57,200
 - Really? Who's that, then?
 GERRl: Tom!

372
00:23:59,880 --> 00:24:02,880
 l like to get on the train...

373
00:24:03,120 --> 00:24:06,120
 But, you see,
 the car is cheaper than the train, isn't it?

374
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:11,160
 GERRl:
 Not environmentally.

375
00:24:11,200 --> 00:24:13,319
 Oh, what you mean...?
 (bangs feet on floor)

376
00:24:13,320 --> 00:24:15,439
 (laughs)

377
00:24:15,440 --> 00:24:18,039
 Those are my carbon footprints, Gerri.

378
00:24:18,040 --> 00:24:21,040
 - Yes, l know.
 - (giggles drunkenly)

379
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:24,960
 Financially, cars are cheaper.
 That's why there's no incentive to go by train.

380
00:24:26,080 --> 00:24:28,279
 Well, what about the airlines?

381
00:24:28,280 --> 00:24:31,280
 No government wants to increase
 the duty on aviation fuel.

382
00:24:32,400 --> 00:24:33,679
 No.

383
00:24:33,680 --> 00:24:36,159
 And this government
 won't invest in the railways,

384
00:24:36,160 --> 00:24:37,999
 so anything we do is a piss in the ocean.

385
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:39,159
 Absolutely.

386
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:41,279
 And then there's the big corporations,

387
00:24:41,280 --> 00:24:43,999
 who keep their lights on all night
 in empty office blocks.

388
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:46,559
 We're all expected to do our bit with eco bulbs.

389
00:24:46,560 --> 00:24:49,559
 l know.

390
00:24:49,560 --> 00:24:52,560
 Should l stop recycling, then, Gerri?

391
00:24:52,760 --> 00:24:54,879
 - No.
 TOM: You've got to set an example.

392
00:24:54,880 --> 00:24:57,759
 - Yeah.
 - Plant a few tomatoes.

393
00:24:57,760 --> 00:25:00,760
 And courgettes.

394
00:25:01,680 --> 00:25:04,680
 l am very environmentally friendly, actually.

395
00:25:05,920 --> 00:25:07,799
 - Are you?
 - Yeah.

396
00:25:07,800 --> 00:25:10,279
 l don't fly.

397
00:25:10,280 --> 00:25:13,280
 l don't live in a house
 that's more than l need.

398
00:25:14,600 --> 00:25:16,199
 l don't cook.

399
00:25:16,200 --> 00:25:19,079
 - Other people cook for you, though.
 - Who?

400
00:25:19,080 --> 00:25:20,719
 You get takeaways, don't you?

401
00:25:20,720 --> 00:25:23,720
 That doesn't count.
 Everybody gets takeaways.

402
00:25:24,360 --> 00:25:27,360
 You've built whole motorways, Tom.

403
00:25:27,560 --> 00:25:30,279
 How environmentally friendly is that?

404
00:25:30,280 --> 00:25:31,439
 Exactly!

405
00:25:31,440 --> 00:25:34,440
 More cars! More cars!
 At least l'm buying an old car.

406
00:25:35,400 --> 00:25:36,999
 - Recycled.
 - Yeah.

407
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 Yet we're constantly told that
 the measure of a thriving economy

408
00:25:41,080 --> 00:25:43,559
 is the sale of new cars.

409
00:25:43,560 --> 00:25:46,119
 Yes, but, Tom...

410
00:25:46,120 --> 00:25:49,120
 ..if l buy a new car...

411
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:52,959
 ..that's another car.

412
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:55,960
 You're absolutely right, Mary.

413
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:59,440
 And would you like some coffee?

414
00:26:01,320 --> 00:26:02,839
 No, thank you.

415
00:26:02,840 --> 00:26:05,840
 l'd like my usual.

416
00:26:17,640 --> 00:26:19,239
 Are you all right, Gerri?

417
00:26:19,240 --> 00:26:21,319
 Yes, Mary, l'm fine.

418
00:26:21,320 --> 00:26:24,320
 How are you?

419
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:29,159
 l'm happy.

420
00:26:29,160 --> 00:26:32,160
 Good.

421
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:36,760
 l just wanted to say...

422
00:26:36,880 --> 00:26:39,880
 ..that if you ever need to share anything...

423
00:26:41,960 --> 00:26:44,960
 ..l'm here for you.

424
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:49,799
 l'm a very good listener.

425
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:51,639
 Thank you, Mary, but l'm fine.

426
00:26:51,640 --> 00:26:54,640
 Yeah, l know.

427
00:27:06,680 --> 00:27:09,680
 lt's very kind of you, Mary.

428
00:27:12,200 --> 00:27:15,200
 Oh, Gerri.

429
00:27:17,640 --> 00:27:20,640
 Everybody needs someone to talk to,
 don't they?

430
00:27:22,360 --> 00:27:25,360
 Yes, Mary, they do.

431
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:31,680
 Oh, well, onwards and upwards.

432
00:27:32,880 --> 00:27:34,439
 You'd better stay the night.

433
00:27:34,440 --> 00:27:36,199
 No. No.

434
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:38,919
 Well, l think you should.

435
00:27:38,920 --> 00:27:40,879
 All right, Gerri, you're the boss.

436
00:27:40,880 --> 00:27:43,879
 We'll find you a T-shirt again.

437
00:27:43,880 --> 00:27:46,880
 Will you?

438
00:27:50,160 --> 00:27:52,679
 l've found you a toothbrush.

439
00:27:52,680 --> 00:27:55,680
 l sometimes wonder what he's doing.

440
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:58,919
 lf he thinks about me. l bet he does.

441
00:27:58,920 --> 00:28:01,920
 GERRl:
 How old was he?

442
00:28:02,320 --> 00:28:04,679
 He'll be 64 now.

443
00:28:04,680 --> 00:28:07,159
 TOM: 64?
 Blimey, he's older than me.

444
00:28:07,160 --> 00:28:09,559
 - Almost a pensioner.
 TOM: He'll be past it now, Mary.

445
00:28:09,560 --> 00:28:11,479
 - Give us your hand.
 - Oh, no, Tom.

446
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:13,039
 He was lovely.

447
00:28:13,040 --> 00:28:15,239
 Well, we all grow old.

448
00:28:15,240 --> 00:28:18,240
 Oh, no, but he was very, very, sexy, Gerri.
 Do you know what l mean?

449
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:22,079
 TOM:
 Too much information.

450
00:28:22,080 --> 00:28:25,080
 l bet he regrets it deep down.

451
00:28:25,240 --> 00:28:28,240
 l hope he does.

452
00:28:28,280 --> 00:28:31,280
 He was my big love...

453
00:28:31,640 --> 00:28:34,640
 ..but he was married.

454
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:38,399
 Well, what can you do, Tom?

455
00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:41,400
 You can't walk around
 with a label saying,

456
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:44,800
 ''Don't fall in love with me,
 l'm married,'' can you?

457
00:28:45,160 --> 00:28:46,839
 Some people wear a ring.

458
00:28:46,840 --> 00:28:49,679
 He didn't.

459
00:28:49,680 --> 00:28:52,680
 But he wasn't a bad person.

460
00:28:56,480 --> 00:28:59,039
 He loved me.

461
00:28:59,040 --> 00:29:02,040
 Sounds to me
 like he was a duplicitous shit.

462
00:29:02,120 --> 00:29:05,120
 GERRl:
 Tom?

463
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:12,679
 Do you think it was my fault, Tom?

464
00:29:12,680 --> 00:29:15,399
 No, l don't, Mary.

465
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:16,799
 Honest.

466
00:29:16,800 --> 00:29:19,119
 lt takes two to tango.

467
00:29:19,120 --> 00:29:21,839
 Oh, so you think it was my fault, Gerri?

468
00:29:21,840 --> 00:29:24,840
 - l didn't say that.
 - No, l know you didn't, really.

469
00:29:28,200 --> 00:29:30,639
 l blame my big heart.

470
00:29:30,640 --> 00:29:33,640
 Well, we all have to make choices,
 don't we?

471
00:29:35,400 --> 00:29:38,400
 Why do l always get it wrong, Gerri?

472
00:29:42,440 --> 00:29:45,440
 l mean, look what happened
 when l got divorced from that shit.

473
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:50,000
 l let him palm me offwith 5,000...
 nothing pounds

474
00:29:52,040 --> 00:29:53,839
 and what am l left with now?

475
00:29:53,840 --> 00:29:56,559
 Sod all.

476
00:29:56,560 --> 00:29:59,560
 l'm living in a poky rented flat when
 l should have my own home at my age.

477
00:30:05,720 --> 00:30:08,720
 lt's not fair.

478
00:30:18,040 --> 00:30:21,040
 Bastard.

479
00:30:43,160 --> 00:30:45,079
 My goodness.

480
00:30:45,080 --> 00:30:46,679
 Hm?

481
00:30:46,680 --> 00:30:49,680
 - She gets worse.
 - l know. Desperate.

482
00:30:52,840 --> 00:30:55,839
 l feel a bit guilty.

483
00:30:55,840 --> 00:30:57,479
 What?

484
00:30:57,480 --> 00:30:59,119
 Well, you know.

485
00:30:59,120 --> 00:31:02,120
 No.

486
00:31:04,920 --> 00:31:07,920
 No. You're right.

487
00:31:10,160 --> 00:31:13,160
 l don't think l really enjoyed history at school.

488
00:31:13,800 --> 00:31:15,719
 Didn't you?

489
00:31:15,720 --> 00:31:18,720
 Maybe l did.

490
00:31:20,520 --> 00:31:23,520
 lt's just that the older you get,
 the more relevant it seems.

491
00:31:23,600 --> 00:31:25,279
 Hm.

492
00:31:25,280 --> 00:31:28,280
 To state the bleeding obvious.

493
00:31:35,480 --> 00:31:37,359
 We'll be part of history soon.

494
00:31:37,360 --> 00:31:40,360
 Exactly.

495
00:31:41,840 --> 00:31:44,519
 - Aha!
 - Aha!

